<br>
The Bloodgill Goblins inside the Lake of Ill Omen.<br>
<br>
The Goblins will start to green out (exp green) at 48th though most will still be blue, and the burning woods is better exps once you get the 49th level spells.<br>
<br>
In the middle of the lake is a large hill underwater.  It is basically a round hump underwater (A large white hump of stone underwater).  At each of the four corners of the hill, is a spawn of two Bloodgill Goblins.  They range in level from 34th to 38th level.  They are always warrior mobs (not spell castors), and they only have about 1500 hitpoints.  Max hits are around 70 to 80 damage.<br>
<br>
A solo druid can be very successful in hunting these using a Root/DoT method.  Quad Kiting is possible, but is WAY to problematical.  Pulling mobs from underwater to land is VERY difficult.  Usually you will only serve to aggro the mobs, and perhaps leave a Bloodgill roaming on the land above creating a nasty mob that will slaughter the lower levels hunting above.  (kind of like a wandering specter in the Oasis)<br>
<br>
This method is very workable.<br>
<br>
- First, bring a lot of batwings and fish scales (or some other breath-underwater device).<br>
- Next, use the area at the top of the “hill” underwater to meditate.  Nothing will spawn near here, and you will be safe.<br>
<br>
(HELPFUL HINT: If you are underwater and wish to surface and be levitating above the water use this simple trick.  Cast levitate (or be levitating in the first place), then use the PAGE UP button all the way so that you are looking straight up.  Then press the forward arrow key to surface WHILE also pressing either the RIGHT or LEFT arrow key making you SPIN upward.  Once you surface let go of the forward arrow key, but keep holding down the RIGHT or LEFT arrow key until you make another complete 360 degree turn.  This will make sure that you will be fully outside the water, and able to regain your stamina from swimming.  Simply press HOME to level your vision again.)<br>
<br>
Solo Hunting guide for Bloodgill Goblins:<br>
<br>
Chosen spells to memorize: GHEAL, GATE, IMMOLIATE, DRIFTING DEATH, ROOT, FIRESTRIKE, SNARE (not ensnare), HARMONY.<br>
<br>
Usually I alternated between two corners.  This assured me that fresh spawns would be up every time I was ready to pull.<br>
<br>
Start by casting a fresh Enduring Breath/Levitate.  Then enter the water from the top of the hill and proceed to a corner.  Find the 2 goblins at that corner swimming together in close proximity.  Target the one farther away from the hill and cast HARMONY.  Ensure that the glowing aura of harmony appears below him.  Then target the non-Harmonized goblin and swim a bit back up the hill (its OK if that goblin is not in view, as long as it is inside snare range).  Snare that goblin and immediately cast ROOT.  This will root the goblin in the water near you and bring him away from the other goblin.  Cast both Immolate and Drifting Death, then swim up the hill a bit more (do not get out of range of the goblin or he will teleport to you when root breaks.  Usually swim only a few more feet up the mountain, but sometimes you do not have to even do that, it just depends on how close the goblin got to you before being rooted (it takes practice.))<br>
<br>
Eventually Root will break, and you will have to Re-Root.  You can choose to cast DRIFTING DEATH again, or Firestrike/Root to finish the goblin off.<br>
<br>
Once the first goblin is dead, make sure you have at least 60 percent mana left and full hp, and pull the second.  Fight this one the same way.<br>
<br>
Once you are finished with the 2 goblins at that corner, return to the top of the underwater hill.  Surface, and meditate.  When you are full mana go to the second spire and repeat. Usually I had to replace Levitate every spire, but my other buffs would last for 4 kills before needing to be reapplied.<br>
<br>
NOTES:<br>
<br>
- I used snare rather then ensnare to save a bit of mana, since you only snare to pull it away from its partner and not to kite.<br>
- There are a few more Bloodgills down below, but these are hard to see, and I feel that they are harder to handle then the spire spawns.<br>
- Faction hits are negative with goblins (who cares), and positive with the Pirates of Gunthak.  I have not seen the Pirates yet, but I have killed enough of these to be nominated the new captain I am sure =).<br>
- Be sure you practice your underwater fighting skill a bit before you try this.  Fight some of the lesser fish in Kedge Keep to practice this style, as you will get interrupted a LOT more underwater (since any hit by the creature will move you and cause you to be interrupted.)  Also you will need to wait a BIT longer after you stop moving to be able to cast a spell (you stay moving longer underwater.)  Fighting on the hill is best, as you will always have land underneath you.  Otherwise the sinking into the water will cause you to be interrupted.<br>
- Loot is only average.  Research components, and plat.  The most common drop is an ancient coin for the bard tambourine quest (worth 6 cp at a vender).  A VERY rare drop is the Harpoon of the Depth (the goblins never loot weapons, so if you see one with a spear congratulate yourself), it currently sells for about 1,000pp.  Same ratio as Yak, but no proc.<br>
